## Introduction to Java
Java is a high-level, object-oriented, platform-independent programming language that follows the 'Write Once, Run Anywhere' (WORA) principle through the Java Virtual Machine (JVM). This means code written once can run on any platform that has Java installed.

### Key Characteristics of Java
Java compiles source code into bytecode that can run on any JVM, making it truly platform-independent. Everything in Java is treated as an object except for primitive data types. The language provides automatic garbage collection, which means developers don't need to manually manage memory. Java also has built-in security features and supports multithreading, allowing developers to write programs that perform multiple tasks concurrently.

### Basic Program Structure
```java
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}
```

Every Java application must have at least one class definition. The main method serves as the entry point where program execution begins. When you run a Java program, the JVM looks for the main method to start execution. Java is case-sensitive, which means that 'age' and 'Age' are treated as two different variables. You can write comments in Java using double slashes for single-line comments or slash-asterisk notation for multi-line comments.

Packages in Java help organize classes into logical groups and prevent naming conflicts. You can import classes from packages using the import statement. Access modifiers like public, private, and protected control the visibility of classes and their members. Following naming conventions is important: class names use PascalCase, variable and method names use camelCase, and constant names use UPPER_CASE for better code readability.

## Object-Oriented Programming
Object-oriented programming is the foundation of Java. It helps organize code into reusable components and makes programs easier to maintain and understand.

### Classes and Objects
A class serves as a blueprint for creating objects. When you define a class, you specify what data it will hold and what operations it can perform. An object is a specific instance of a class with actual values.

```java
public class Car {
    private String color;

    public Car(String color) { this.color = color; }
    public void drive() { System.out.println("Driving..."); }
}

Car car = new Car("Red");
car.drive();
```

### Encapsulation
Encapsulation is the practice of hiding internal details of an object and exposing only what is necessary. This is achieved by using private fields and public getter and setter methods. This approach ensures that data cannot be directly modified in an invalid way.

```java
private int age;
public int getAge() { return age; }
public void setAge(int age) { if (age > 0) this.age = age; }
```

### Inheritance
Inheritance allows a class to inherit properties and methods from another class. The child class extends the parent class using the 'extends' keyword. This promotes code reuse and establishes a hierarchical relationship between classes.

```java
public class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void eat() { System.out.println("Dog eats"); }
}
```

### Polymorphism
Polymorphism means 'many forms'. Method overloading occurs at compile-time when you have multiple methods with the same name but different parameters. Method overriding happens at runtime when a child class provides a different implementation of a parent class method.

```java
public int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
public double add(double a, double b) { return a + b; }

Animal dog = new Dog();
dog.eat();  // Calls Dog's eat() method
```

### Abstraction and Interfaces
Abstraction hides implementation details and shows only essential features. An abstract class cannot be instantiated but can define abstract methods that subclasses must implement. An interface is a contract that specifies what methods a class must implement.

```java
public abstract class Shape {
    public abstract double getArea();
}

public interface Animal {
    void eat();
}

public class Dog implements Animal {
    @Override public void eat() { }
}
```

### The this and super Keywords
The 'this' keyword refers to the current object instance, allowing you to access its properties and methods. The 'super' keyword refers to the parent class, enabling you to call parent class methods and constructors from within the child class.

## Control Flow Statements
Control flow statements determine the order in which your program executes different parts of code. They allow you to make decisions and repeat actions based on conditions.

### Conditional Statements: if and else
The if statement allows you to execute code only if a condition is true. You can chain multiple else-if statements to check several conditions. The else block executes when no previous conditions were true. These statements are essential for making decisions in your program.

```java
if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Adult");
} else if (age >= 13) {
    System.out.println("Teenager");
} else {
    System.out.println("Child");
}
```

### The switch Statement
The switch statement is useful when you have many possible values to check against. It compares a variable against multiple cases and executes the matching block. The break statement prevents fall-through to the next case. The default case executes if no other cases match.

```java
switch(day) {
    case 1: System.out.println("Monday"); break;
    case 2: System.out.println("Tuesday"); break;
    default: System.out.println("Other");
}
```

### The Ternary Operator
The ternary operator provides a concise way to write simple if-else statements on a single line. The condition is evaluated first, then either the first or second expression is returned based on whether it is true or false.

```java
String status = (age >= 18) ? "Adult" : "Minor";
```

### Loop Constructs
The traditional for loop executes a block of code a specific number of times. It initializes a counter, checks a condition, and increments the counter after each iteration. The enhanced for loop, also called for-each, iterates through arrays and collections without managing indices. The while loop repeats as long as a condition remains true. The do-while loop executes at least once before checking the condition.

### Breaking Out and Skipping Iterations
The break statement immediately exits a loop, stopping further iterations. The continue statement skips the current iteration and proceeds to the next one. These statements give you fine control over loop behavior.

### Logical Operators
The AND operator (&&) requires both conditions to be true. The OR operator (||) requires at least one condition to be true. The NOT operator (!) negates a boolean value. Comparison operators include equals (==), not equals (!=), greater than (>), less than (<), and their variants with equals.

## Understanding Collections
The Collections Framework provides a set of classes and interfaces for storing and manipulating groups of objects. Collections are more flexible than arrays because they can grow and shrink dynamically.

### Lists: Ordered Collections
Lists are ordered collections that maintain the insertion order and allow duplicate values. You can access elements by their index position. ArrayList is the most commonly used implementation and provides fast random access. You can add elements at the end or at a specific position. You can remove elements by index or by value. The contains method checks if an element exists in the list.

```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add("Apple");  list.add("Banana");
list.add(1, "Orange");  // Insert at position 1
String first = list.get(0);
list.remove(0);
list.remove("Apple");
boolean exists = list.contains("Banana");
```

### Sets: Unique Collections
Sets are unordered collections that do not allow duplicate values. HashSet provides fast lookup but does not maintain order. TreeSet keeps elements in sorted order. Sets are useful when you need to ensure uniqueness of elements.

```java
Set<String> set = new HashSet<>();
set.add("Apple");  set.add("Apple");  // Duplicate ignored
Set<Integer> sorted = new TreeSet<>();  // Maintains order
```

### Maps: Key-Value Collections
Maps store pairs of keys and values, where each key is unique. HashMap provides fast lookup based on the key. You can retrieve values by their key. The containsKey method checks if a key exists. The containsValue method checks if a value exists. TreeMap keeps entries sorted by key.

```java
Map<String, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
map.put("Apple", 5);
Integer value = map.get("Apple");
map.containsKey("Banana");
map.remove("Apple");
for (String key : map.keySet()) { System.out.println(key); }
```

### Queues: FIFO Collections
Queues follow the First-In-First-Out principle. PriorityQueue orders elements based on priority rather than insertion order. You can add elements and retrieve the next element based on the queue's ordering.

### Collections Utility Methods
The sort method arranges elements in ascending order. The reverse method reverses the order of elements. The shuffle method randomizes the order. The min and max methods find the smallest and largest elements. The frequency method counts how many times an element appears.

## Understanding Exceptions
Exceptions are events that disrupt the normal flow of program execution. Proper exception handling prevents your program from crashing and allows you to respond gracefully to errors.

### Exception Categories
Checked exceptions must be caught or declared in the method signature. Examples include IOException and SQLException. Unchecked exceptions, also called runtime exceptions, do not require catching. Examples include NullPointerException and ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException. Errors represent serious problems that programs usually cannot recover from, like StackOverflowError.

### Try-Catch-Finally Blocks
The try block contains code that might throw an exception. The catch block handles the exception if it occurs. You can have multiple catch blocks for different exception types. The finally block always executes regardless of whether an exception was thrown. This is useful for cleanup operations like closing files.

```java
try {
    int result = 10 / 0;  // Throws ArithmeticException
} catch (ArithmeticException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: " + e.getMessage());
    e.printStackTrace();
} finally {
    System.out.println("Cleanup code");
}
```

### Multi-Catch and Try-with-Resources
In Java 7 and later, you can catch multiple exception types in a single catch block using the pipe operator. Try-with-resources automatically closes resources that implement AutoCloseable, eliminating the need for explicit cleanup.

```java
try {
    // Code
} catch (NullPointerException | ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    System.out.println("Caught an exception");
}

try (FileReader fr = new FileReader("file.txt")) {
    // Use resource
} catch (IOException e) {
    System.out.println("Error reading file");
}  // Automatically closed
```

### Throwing and Declaring Exceptions
You can manually throw an exception using the throw keyword. You can declare that a method might throw an exception using the throws keyword. This tells callers that they need to handle the exception.

### Creating Custom Exceptions
You can create your own exception classes by extending the Exception class. This allows you to define meaningful error types specific to your application.

```java
public class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
    public InvalidAgeException(String msg) { super(msg); }
}

if (age < 0) throw new InvalidAgeException("Age must be positive");
```

## Multithreading Fundamentals
Multithreading allows multiple tasks to run concurrently within a single program. This is useful for responsive user interfaces and efficient use of computer resources. Each thread is a separate path of execution within the same program.

### Creating Threads
You can create a thread by extending the Thread class and overriding the run method. The run method contains the code that executes in the thread. You must call the start method to begin execution, not the run method directly. Alternatively, you can implement the Runnable interface, which is preferred because Java does not support multiple inheritance. This approach is more flexible.

```java
public class MyThread extends Thread {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            System.out.println("Thread " + i);
            try { Thread.sleep(1000); } catch (InterruptedException e) {}
        }
    }
}

MyThread t = new MyThread();
t.start();  // Start the thread

Thread t = new Thread(() -> System.out.println("Running"));
t.start();
```

### Thread Methods
The start method begins thread execution. The join method makes the current thread wait for another thread to finish. The sleep method pauses execution for a specified time. You can set and get thread names for identification. Priority can be set from 1 to 10, with higher numbers having higher priority. The isAlive method checks if a thread is still running.

### Synchronization
When multiple threads access shared data, synchronization ensures that only one thread accesses it at a time. A synchronized method locks the entire object. A synchronized block locks only a specific portion of code, providing finer control. This prevents data corruption and unexpected behavior.

```java
public synchronized void increment() { count++; }

synchronized(lock) { count++; }
```

### Inter-Thread Communication
Threads can communicate with each other using wait and notify methods. The wait method causes a thread to pause until another thread calls notify. This is useful for producer-consumer patterns where one thread produces data and another consumes it.

### The volatile Keyword
The volatile keyword ensures that changes to a variable are visible to all threads. Without it, a thread might use a cached value instead of the current value.

### Executor Framework
The Executor Framework provides a high-level interface for managing threads. Instead of creating individual threads, you submit tasks to an executor service. It manages a pool of threads for you, improving performance and making code cleaner.

### Callable and Future
Callable is similar to Runnable but can return a value. Future represents the result of an asynchronous computation that will be available in the future. You can retrieve the result using the get method, which blocks until the result is ready.
